# However we want to see correlation in graphical representation so below is function for that
def plot_corr(df, size=15):
    corr = df.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size, size))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.1f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')

BankData_X = BankData.drop('Personal Loan',axis=1)  # Dropping Personal Loan column
BankData_Y = BankData['Personal Loan'] #Target variable


BankData_X_train, BankData_X_test, BankData_Y_train, BankData_Y_test = train_test_split(BankData_X, BankData_Y, test_size = 0.3, random_state = 1)
